sql:
SELECT benchmark_name, benchmark_return
FROM fund_benchmarks
WHERE benchmark_type = 'Equity';

external_knowledge:
- "seasoned gardeners" refers to fund managers with more than 5 years of experience;
- "fertile soil of low-cost managed funds" refers to funds with an annual expense ratio less than 0.015;
- "average growth of the seeds" refers to the average Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) return.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM fund_performance_reports 
WHERE report_type = 'quarterly' AND report_status = 'published';

SELECT AVG(nav) 
FROM fund_historical_prices 
WHERE fund_id = 1;

SELECT COUNT(period_id) 
FROM performance_data 
WHERE cagr_return > (SELECT AVG(cagr_return) FROM performance_data);

external_knowledge:
- CAGR (Compound Annual Growth Rate) is a measure of the mean annual growth rate of an investment over a specified time period longer than one year.;
- Alpha is a measure of the active return on an investment, the performance relative to a benchmark index.;
- Sharpe ratio is a measure of the return of an investment compared to its risk, calculated by dividing the excess return by the standard deviation of the return.;
- NAV (Net Asset Value) is the value of a fund’s assets minus its liabilities, divided by the number of shares outstanding.

- "Top-performing funds" refers to funds with the highest CAGR return over a 1-year period;
- "Top assets" refers to the assets with the highest percentage of the fund's total assets;
- "Most experienced managers" refers to the fund managers with the most years of experience.

